{Agreed that the bidding wasn't much. The final contract is still a good one. West is to play 6\H. North leads the \SJ.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=0  \D=0  \C=4  Total = 4

There really aren't 4 \C losers since they can be ruffed in dummy. In fact you should see that this is an ideal cross-ruff hand, ruffing \Cs in dummy and \Ds in your hand. Since neither hand can be over-ruffed you expect to make all 8 trumps.

Remember, when playing a cross ruff, you need to take any side suit winners first, otherwise a defender may be able to discard that suit while you are ruffing. So you win the \SA, then take the \SK, then . . . what? 

Losers:   \S=0  \H=0  \D=0  \C=4  Total = 4

There really aren't 4 \C losers since they can be ruffed in dummy. In fact you should see that this is an ideal cross-ruff hand, ruffing \Cs in dummy and \Ds in your hand. Since neither hand can be over-ruffed you expect to make all 8 trumps.

Remember, when playing a cross ruff, you need to take any side suit winners first, otherwise a defender may be able to discard that suit while you are ruffing. So you win the \SA, then take the \SK, then . . . what?

Well, if you win the \SQ, then the two Minor suit Aces, you'd be set up to cross-ruff the hand out for all 13 tricks. But here's what might happen if you try.

South might ruff the \SQ. OK, no disaster yet. But he might then play a trump. Your slam is now kaput. You can no longer make 8 trump tricks and will end up down 1. 

The answer is to not be greedy for that overtrick. With North's opening \S lead there is an indication of possible length there. So, realizing that South could be short in the suit, take just the 2 \S tricks that you need for the slam, then play your Minor Aces and start the cross-ruff.

When playing a cross-ruff you must take all the side-suit winners you need early so they won't get ruffed later.

Don't jeopardize your contract trying to take too many. }
[Play "W"]SJ

